			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~thegarbz">thegarbz</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~thegarbz">( 1787294 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64146185"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64146185"><p><div class="quote"><p>Plenty of research has shown that giving poor people money doesn&#226;(TM)t help, it hurts them.</p></div><p>Nope it really hasn't. Quite the opposite, virtually all research has shown that the poor (we're talking here about people who can't freely afford basic internet) are in a locked loop of being too poor to better themselves due to not having the basic finances required for reskilling or finding other work, and the only way they are able to get out of it is with a minimal amount of assistance.</p><p>But keep living in your right wing fantasy world.</p><p><div class="quote"><p>As others here pointed out, it&#226;(TM)s $30 on a $120 broadband connection when the market already has $20 and $25 options in most markets this is targeting.</p></div><p>Now your republican fantasy thinks you can get internet for sub $30 e<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

