		<div id="comment_body_64146201"><p><div class="quote"><p>Seems to it should pick one side</p></div><p>No it shouldn't. Different sides of funding cause different effects on a market, especially when that funding is conditional. Expanding and upgrading broadband does nothing to bring down costs for those who can't afford it, covering costs for those who can afford it does nothing to expand and upgrade a network.</p><p><div class="quote"><p>It's like we're subsidizing buying tickets for the local NFL franchise, and also paying for the players salary (the locals cover the cost of the stadium!)...</p></div><p>Funny you should say that. The former increases attendance and interest in a sport, the latter (in a world of buying talent) improves the chances for a local team providing potential fame and tourism<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
